 To make an HTTP request in JavaScript, you can use the `XMLHttpRequest` object or the more modern `fetch()` API. Here's an example of both methods:

Using `XMLHttpRequest`:
```javascript
const xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();

// Open a new request, specifying the type (GET), the URL, and async (true)
xhr.open('GET', 'https://api.example.com/data', true);

// Set up a function to run when the status changes
xhr.onreadystatechange = function() {
    if (xhr.readyState === 4 && xhr.status === 200) {
        console.log(xhr.responseText);
    }
};

// Send the request
xhr.send();
```

Using `fetch()` (recommended for modern browsers):
```javascript
fetch('https://api.example.com/data')
    .then(response => {
        if (!response.ok) {
            throw new Error('Network response was not ok');
        }
        return response.json(); // or response.text() depending on the response type
    })
    .then(data => {
        console.log(data);
    })
    .catch(error => {
        console.error('There was an error!', error);
    });
```

